    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1931-03-27T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1931-03-27T04:00:00-05:00" n="965"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d965">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.5211/34: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1931-03-27T17:00:00+08:00"
                            >March 27, 1931—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received March 27—9:25 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>172. Reference Senior Minister’s circular No. 20 of March 20 [<hi rend="italic"
                        >4</hi>], 1930.<note n="6" xml:id="d965fn6">Not printed.</note> Following
                    has been received from Hankow: <quote rend="blockquote">
                        <p>“March 26, 3 p.m. Vernacular newspapers have published a proclamation
                            issued by the Bureau of Finance of the Hankow Municipal Government
                            requiring the submission of white deeds<note n="7" xml:id="d965fn7"
                                >Contracts between individual parties.</note> for stamping<note
                                n="8" xml:id="d965fn8">When so approved, the deeds become “red
                                deeds.”</note>
                            <pb facs="1141" n="1031" xml:id="pg_1031"/> before April 1, failing
                            which a fine is to be imposed. I have received no official notice of
                            this requirement. Owners of white deeds hesitate to submit them for
                            stamping and in view of Legation’s circular instructions No. 393 of
                            December 13, 1929, and No. 5 of February 14, 1930,<note n="9"
                                xml:id="d965fn9">Neither printed.</note> I respectfully request
                            telegraphic instructions as to what advice should be given holders of
                            white deeds that have not been stamped of which there are a considerable
                            number recorded in this consular jurisdiction.”</p>
                    </quote>
                </p>
                <p>Department’s telegraphic instructions are requested as soon as possible.</p>
                <closer>For the Minister:<lb/>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Perkins</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
